Let us load the data¶

Note:

  • You must download the dataset from the link provided on Olympus and upload the same on your Google drive before executing the code in the next cell.
  • In case of any error, please make sure that the path of the file is correct as the path may be different for you.
In [3]:
#Storing the path of the data file from the Google drive
path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/cell_images.zip'

#The data is provided as a zip file so we need to extract the files from the zip file
with zipfile.ZipFile(path, 'r') as zip_ref:
    zip_ref.extractall()

The files have been extracted to the local session of Google Colab. The extracted folder would have the following structure:

The extracted folder has different folders for train and test data which further contains the different sizes of images for parasitized and uninfected cells within the respective folder name.

The size of all images must be the same and should be converted to 4D arrays so that they can be used as an input for the convolutional neural network. Also, we need to create the labels for both types of images to be able to train and test the model.

Let's do the same for the training data first and then we will use the same code for the test data as well.

In [4]:
#Storing the path of the extracted "train" folder 
train_dir = '/content/cell_images/train'

#Size of image so that each image has the same size
SIZE = 64

#Empty list to store the training images after they are converted to NumPy arrays
train_images = []

#Empty list to store the training labels (0 - uninfected, 1 - parasitized)
train_labels = []
In [5]:
#We will run the same code for "parasitized" as well as "uninfected" folders within the "train" folder
for folder_name in ['/parasitized/', '/uninfected/']:
    
    #Path of the folder
    images_path = os.listdir(train_dir + folder_name)

    for i, image_name in enumerate(images_path):
        try:
            #Opening each image using the path of that image
            image = Image.open(train_dir + folder_name + image_name)

            #Resizing each image to (224,224)
            image = image.resize((SIZE, SIZE))

            #Converting images to arrays and appending that array to the empty list defined above
            train_images.append(np.array(image))

            #Creating labels for parasitized and uninfected images
            if folder_name=='/parasitized/':
                train_labels.append(1)
            else:
                train_labels.append(0)
        except Exception:
            pass       

#Converting lists to arrays
train_images = np.array(train_images)
train_labels = np.array(train_labels)
In [6]:
#Storing the path of the extracted "test" folder 
test_dir = '/content/cell_images/test'

#Size of image so that each image has the same size (it must be same as the train image size)
SIZE = 64

#Empty list to store the testing images after they are converted to NumPy arrays
test_images = []

#Empty list to store the testing labels (0 - uninfected, 1 - parasitized)
test_labels = []
In [7]:
#We will run the same code for "parasitized" as well as "uninfected" folders within the "test" folder
for folder_name in ['/parasitized/', '/uninfected/']:
    
    #Path of the folder
    images_path = os.listdir(test_dir + folder_name)

    for i, image_name in enumerate(images_path):
        try:
            #Opening each image using the path of that image
            image = Image.open(test_dir + folder_name + image_name)
            
            #Resizing each image to (128,128)
            image = image.resize((SIZE, SIZE))
            
            #Converting images to arrays and appending that array to the empty list defined above
            test_images.append(np.array(image))
            
            #Creating labels for parasitized and uninfected images
            if folder_name=='/parasitized/':
                test_labels.append(1)
            else:
                test_labels.append(0)
        except Exception:
            pass       

#Converting lists to arrays
test_images = np.array(test_images)
test_labels = np.array(test_labels)

Plotting the train and validation curves

In [18]:
# function to plot train and validation accuracy 
def plot_accuracy(history):
    N = len(history.history["accuracy"])
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history.history["accuracy"], label="train_accuracy", ls='--')
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history.history["val_accuracy"], label="val_accuracy", ls='--')
    plt.title("Accuracy vs Epoch")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")
In [19]:
plot_accuracy(history)
  • Here we can clearly observe that the training and valiation accuracy are increasing
  • And we can also notice that validation accuracy is slightly higher than the train accuracy

Building the Model

In [21]:
#creating sequential model
model1=Sequential()

# Build the model here
# Adding two more filter layers with increased number of filters:
model1.add(Conv2D(filters=64,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu",input_shape=(64,64,3))) #starting with 64 filters
model1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model1.add(Dropout(0.2))

model1.add(Conv2D(filters=64,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model1.add(Dropout(0.2))

model1.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model1.add(Dropout(0.2))

model1.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model1.add(Dropout(0.2))

model1.add(Flatten())

#Adding one additional dense layer to make the transition from 512 to 2 smoother
model1.add(Dense(512,activation="relu"))
model1.add(Dropout(0.4))

model1.add(Dense(256,activation="relu"))
model1.add(Dropout(0.4))

model1.add(Dense(2,activation="softmax"))#2 represent output layer neurons 

model1.summary()

Model 2 with Batch Normalization

Building the Model

Since adding extra layers did not change the performance of the model, we revert to the original base model using Batch Normalization and Leaky Relu. It is always good practice in machine learning data science to keep model small for better performance if there is no tangible benefit in making it bigger.

In [120]:
model2 = Sequential()

model2.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), input_shape=(64, 64, 3), padding='same'))
model2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
model2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())

model2.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
model2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())

model2.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
model2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())

model2.add(Flatten())

model2.add(Dense(512))
model2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

Observations and insights:
  • Using Batch Normalization and Leacky Relu does not seem to hugely impact the perfomance of the model.
  • The validation accuracy here seems a bit less stable compared to the other two models.
  • Once there is big dip in the validation accuracy, that's a sign of overfitting in this model.
  • The all-important test data accuracy stays around 95% which is pretty decent but consistent with the base model and the bigger model with more layers.
  • One reason the tweaking of the models doesn't seem to improve the perfomance is the fact that the base model could be pretty sufficient to classify images.
  • This stems from the fact that the malaria images are not very feature-rich and the parasitized images only have small dots in them. In a more complex image, additional CNN layers (both filter and flattened) could help improve the performance. However, here, wich these simple images, this is not the case.
  • Nontheless, amongst the three models, we should probably go with the one that gives least false negatives, as that is a more imprtant factor. In this case, it would be the second model with more layers. Avoiding false negatives in healthcase is very important and models should try to reasonably do so.

Using image data generator

In [135]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(train_images, train_labels, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

# Using ImageDataGenerator to generate images

train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip=True, 
                                  zoom_range = 0.5, rotation_range=30)
val_datagen  = ImageDataGenerator()

# Flowing training images using train_datagen generator
train_generator = train_datagen.flow(x = X_train, y = y_train, batch_size=64, seed=42, shuffle=True)     

# Flowing validation images using val_datagen generator
val_generator =  val_datagen.flow(x= X_val, y = y_val, batch_size=64, seed=42, shuffle=True)

Observations and insights:
  • The code has done some transformations to the images according to these parameters: (horizontal_flip=True, zoom_range = 0.5, rotation_range=30)
  • Some of these transformations are difficult to decipher. For instance, horizontal flip and rotation are hard to see as the original images do have some left-right as well as rotational symmetry.
  • However, the zoom effect is more clearly visible. Some images have exploded to fill in a larger spece and have more pixels. Other images have shrunk.
  • Overall, this is a good practive to prevent overfitting and make the model more robust and more stable.

Building the Model

In [53]:
model3 = Sequential()

# Build the model here
model3.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu",input_shape=(64,64,3)))
model3.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model3.add(Dropout(0.2))

model3.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model3.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model3.add(Dropout(0.2))

model3.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model3.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model3.add(Dropout(0.2))

model3.add(Flatten())

model3.add(Dense(512,activation="relu"))
model3.add(Dropout(0.4))

model3.add(Dense(2,activation="softmax")) 
# use this as the optimizer
adam = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001)

model3.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=adam, metrics = ['accuracy'])
model3.summary()

transfer_layer = vgg.get_layer('block5_pool')
vgg.trainable=False

# Add classification layers on top of it  
 
x = Flatten()(transfer_layer.output) #Flatten the output from the 3rd block of the VGG16 model
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)

# Similarly add a dense layer with 128 neurons
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)

x = Dropout(0.3)(x)

# Add a dense layer with 64 neurons
x = Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)


x = BatchNormalization()(x)
pred = Dense(2, activation='softmax')(x)

model4 = Model(vgg.input, pred) #Initializing the model
model4.summary()

  • Choose the model with the best accuracy scores from all the above models and save it as a final model.

Observations and Conclusions drawn from the final model:

  • As discussed above, VGG is a large model. It is not really suited for this problem.
  • Large models tend to overfit the data and this is observed from the accuracy curve of the validation data.
  • All models give similar accuracies. The base model along with the extended deeper model, and the model with Leaky Relu and Batch normalization, provide accuracies close to 96%. This is pretty decent.
  • Accordingly, of all these models, the smallest model is the best and most economical.
  • Another big consideration in chosing a model is false negatives. The extended deeper model gives slightly better recall, which is very important in healthcare diagnosis scenarios.

Improvements that can be done:

  • Can the model performance be improved using other pre-trained models or different CNN architecture?
  • ANSWER: It does not seem like the model could be improved much. Whatever is left to be improved would relate to the data quality and not the model. There are apparently some mislabled data in the dataset from what I can see. There are also hard limitations to any CNN or NN model too which may scape our eyes too.

Insights

Insights¶

Refined insights:¶

  • What are the most meaningful insights from the data relevant to the problem?

-*The basic insight about the data are:

1- It is not feature-rich. CNNsmodels do well with feature rich data. They fist extract and and then enhance edges, then reconstruct features and then reconstruct objects. Here, due to simple image data structure, a smaller model does just as well as the bigger models and pre-trained models.

2- The data has limitations. given the consistent number of false negatives and false positives for all models, it is clear that the additional 5% of improvement is due to poor data quality. In a paper by Fuhad et. al. (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7277980/) it is pointed out that the data is mislabled. A good step forward, maybe for milstone-3, would be to get better labels from the literature and run the base model.

Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance:¶

  • How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?

Models seem to be performing at the same level between 93-96% accuracy. The base model, enhanced layers model, and Batch-Norm model all perform essentially at the same level around 95% accuracy on the test data. The VGG is pre-trained and not well suited, and as such, does a little worse. Below, I am bringing and HSV-base model that performs at around 92%, a litttle worse as known in the litrature.

All these point to the fact that the data doesn't have a lot of features and is limited by quality of the data, most likely the mislabeling.

Proposal for the final solution design:¶

  • What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?

Under these circumstances, we could use the smallest model which is most economical and gives consistent results.

If there is critical need for lowest false negatives, and in most clinical cases this is indeed true, we could run each model a few times, take an average of the number of false negatives, and use the model with the lowest number of false negatives. This may indicate that the enhanced base model may be more suitable.

For further study, I would propose finding better data labeling as per the publication: Fuhad et. al. (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7277980/)

modelH.add(BatchNormalization())


modelH.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
modelH.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
modelH.add(Dropout(0.2))
modelH.add(BatchNormalization())

modelH.add(Flatten())

modelH.add(Dense(512,activation="relu"))
modelH.add(Dropout(0.4))
modelH.add(Dense(2,activation="softmax"))#2 represent output layer neurons 
modelH.summary()

As can be seen, the HSV data with the basic model produces 92% accuracy which is decent but less than the RGB data. This is to be expected as per existing literature

The bigger issue with the model, however, is the large amout of fals negatives. If we could reverse this to get higher false positives and very low false negative, this could be very beneficial

This will be an area of exploration, as to how to minimize false negatives at a reasonable cost
